DocumentationGeneral comment This dataset represents the activity of waste disposal of 'refinery sludge' in a sanitary landfill. Recommended use of this dataset: for landfilling of sludge from oil refineries, which goes to disposal as part of communal waste. It is likely that this does not represent a sound disposal for this type of waste and is only tolerable in small amounts. Inventoried waste consists of fraction: 100% refinery sludge; . Waste composition (wet, in ppmw): gross heating value 4.732 MJ/kg; net heating value 2.453 MJ/kg; H2O 888000; O 1017.1; H 13731; C 86452; S 508.54; N 1017.1; P 478.03; B na; Cl na; Br na; F na; I na; Ag na; As na; Ba na; Cd 10.171; Co 20.342; Cr na; Cu 101.71; Hg 2.0342; Mn na; Mo na; Ni 152.56; Pb 457.69; Sb na; Se na; Sn na; V na; Zn 1017.1; Be na; Sc na; Sr na; Ti na; Tl na; W na; Si na; Fe na; Ca 7000; Al na; K na; Mg na; Na na. Share of carbon in initial waste waste that is biogenic 0%. Share of metals in waste not oxidised and bulk-recyclable (exclude very small or thin parts) Iron: 0%; Alu: 0%; Copper: 0%. Overall degradability of waste during 100 years: 60%. Landfill gas capture and utilisation generates 0.03932 kWh of electricity and 0.07091 MJ of useful heat. 0.0004309 kg waste mass remains in the landfill even after the long term period.Technology This is an inventory for a sanitary (controlled) landfill for municipal solid waste. Ultimate average landfill height is 20 meters. Operation phase duration is 30 years. The total raw landfill gas mass produced in the landfill from this waste is 0.05901 kg. The total CH4 mass in the raw landfill gas is 0.05032 kg. Percentage of landfill gas directly emitted is 47w%. Percentage of landfill gas captured and flared is 18.02w%. Percentage of landfill gas captured and utilised is 34.98%. Conversion efficiencies are 27.8e% for electricity and 13.5e% for useful heat.  Leachate collected during the first 100 years is collected and treated region-specifically before emission. Based on average waste composition and climate data the end of carbonate phase is estimated to be reached 2'383 years after waste deposition.Included activities starts The activity starts with the waste being available at the gate of the treatment facility. Collection and transportation of the waste to the treatment plant is not included.Included activities ends The activity ends with the waste being treated and waste-specific emissions from the landfill are released to the environment (air due to landfil gas, water due to landfil leachate, and subsequent into groundwater).Product information 'refinery sludge' is a solid waste under the category of industrial wastes. It is primarily generated in fuel and mineral oil refineries.
'refinery sludge' contain the following fractions: 100% refinery sludge. By the database default (and per unit of reference product),'refinery sludge' has 89.5% water on wet mass basis (10.5% dry matter) and Carbon present is of only fossil origin (76.79% on a dry matter basis). It has a lower heating value of 2.45 MJ/kg .
This kind of by-product (recyclable or waste) is generated from ordinary transforming activities, and as such can be considered for modelling waste outputs of comparable composition.
In the ecoinvent database, treatment option/s for this by-product include: deposition (sanitary landfill, landfarming), thermal (hazardous waste incineration). Based on the aforementioned treatments this by-product receives, it can be both a hazardous and a non-hazardous waste.
This by-product can be modelled on two levels: treatment activity and market activity. The former one refers to the specific technology treating the by-product while the latter level represents a mix of treatments. Users are encouraged to inspect the modelling assumptions of the treatment activities and when selecting the market to additionally inspect the treatment mix.
Collection and transportation of this by-product is accounted in the respective market activity, users are advised to inspect and modify the average transportation distances for a case specific modelling.Geography comment The site has mean annual temperature (MAT) of 9.5 degC, mean annual precipitation (MAP) of 1483.00559816076 mm/year, mean annual actual evaporation (EAT) of 528.63778611689 mm/year, and net infiltration of 954.367812043874 mm/year. he leachate percolating through the landfill has an average residence time of 5.24 years.
